### 3. Real-time AI Features with Bedrock, DynamoDB Streams, and WebSocket APIs
For building interactive AI applications with persistent connections.

```javascript
// WebSocket Connection Handler (Lambda)
const AWS = require('aws-sdk');
const dynamodb = new AWS.DynamoDB.DocumentClient();
const bedrock = new AWS.BedrockRuntime();
const apiGateway = new AWS.ApiGatewayManagementApi({
  endpoint: process.env.WS_API_ENDPOINT
});

exports.handler = async (event) => {
  const connectionId = event.requestContext.connectionId;
  const body = JSON.parse(event.body);

  // Store user context/session in DynamoDB
  await dynamodb.put({
    TableName: process.env.SESSIONS_TABLE,
    Item: {
      connectionId,
      userId: body.userId,
      context: body.initialContext || {},
      createdAt: Date.now()
    }
  }).promise();

  // Send welcome message
  await sendToClient(connectionId, { type: 'CONNECTED', message: 'Ready for AI chat' });

  return { statusCode: 200 };
};

// Separate Lambda triggered by DynamoDB Stream on new messages
exports.processMessage = async (event) => {
  for (const record of event.Records) {
    if (record.eventName === 'INSERT') {
      const message = record.dynamodb.NewImage;
      const session = await getSession(message.connectionId.S);

      // Call Bedrock with conversation history
      const response = await bedrock.invokeModel({
        modelId: 'anthropic.claude-v2',
        contentType: 'application/json',
        accept: 'application/json',
        body: JSON.stringify({
          prompt: `\n\nHuman: ${message.text.S}\n\nAssistant:`,
          max_tokens_to_sample: 1000,
          temperature: 0.7,
          stop_sequences: ['\n\nHuman:']
        })
      }).promise();

      const result = JSON.parse(response.body.toString());

      // Send response via WebSocket
      await sendToClient(message.connectionId.S, {
        type: 'AI_RESPONSE',
        text: result.completion,
        messageId: message.messageId.S
      });
    }
  }
};

async function sendToClient(connectionId, data) {
  try {
    await apiGateway.postToConnection({
      ConnectionId: connectionId,
      Data: JSON.stringify(data)
    }).promise();
  } catch (e) {
    if (e.statusCode === 410) {
      // Remove stale connection
      await dynamodb.delete({
        TableName: process.env.SESSIONS_TABLE,
        Key: { connectionId }
      }).promise();
    }
  }
}
```

## What Interviewers Actually Ask

**Q: Explain how AWS Lambda scales under concurrent requests. What are cold starts and how do you mitigate them?**
**A:** Lambda scales horizontally by creating new execution environments (microVMs) for each concurrent request, up to your account's concurrency limit. Each environment runs one invocation at a time. A **cold start** occurs when Lambda needs to create a new environment: downloading your code, initializing the runtime, and running your initialization code. This adds latency (100ms-2s+). Mitigations include: 1) **Provisioned Concurrency** to keep environments warm, 2) **Optimizing package size** (tree-shaking, minimal dependencies), 3) **Using Lambda SnapStart** for Java, 4) **Keeping functions active** with periodic invocations, and 5) **Initializing SDK clients/connections outside the handler**.

**Q: When would you choose Amazon SageMaker over running your own ML training on EC2 with containers?**
**A:** Choose SageMaker when you want a managed, integrated ML platform that handles infrastructure provisioning, distributed training orchestration, hyperparameter tuning, model deployment, and monitoring out-of-the-box. It's ideal for teams wanting to focus on ML code rather than DevOps. Choose EC2 when you need: 1) Full control over the underlying hardware/OS, 2) Custom scaling logic not supported by SageMaker, 3) To run non-ML workloads alongside training, or 4) To avoid SageMaker's cost premium for very predictable, long-running workloads where reserved EC2 instances would be cheaper.

**Q: You have a Next.js application with real-time AI features. How would you architect this on AWS considering both server-side rendering and WebSocket connections?**
**A:** I'd use a hybrid architecture: 1) **Next.js App** hosted on **Amplify Hosting** or **ECS Fargate** for SSR/SSG capabilities with built-in CI/CD, 2) **API Gateway** (REST) for standard API routes, 3) **API Gateway WebSocket** for real-time connections, with connection state stored in **DynamoDB**, 4) **Lambda functions** behind both APIs for business logic, 5) **Bedrock** or **SageMaker endpoints** for AI inference, 6) **S3** and **CloudFront** for static assets. The WebSocket API maintains persistent connections while server-side rendering happens through the compute service (Amplify/ECS), with both able to invoke the same Lambda functions for consistency.

**Q: How do you secure sensitive data like API keys in AWS, especially for containers running in ECS/EKS?**
**A:** Never hardcode secrets. Use **AWS Secrets Manager** or **Parameter Store (SSM)**. For containers: 1) Inject secrets as environment variables at runtime via ECS task definitions (referencing Secrets Manager ARNs) or EKS using the **Secrets Store CSI driver**, 2) Use **IAM roles for service accounts (IRSA)** in EKS for AWS service permissions, avoiding key usage entirely, 3) For application config, use **Parameter Store** with KMS encryption. Always follow the principle of least privilege in IAM policies and rotate secrets regularly using Secrets Manager's automatic rotation.

